-- Western Refining Extends Maturity on $800 Million of Revolving Credit Line
-- B y   R i c h a r d   B r a v o
-- 2010-12-28T13:58:19Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-28/western-refining-extends-maturity-on-800-million-of-revolving-credit-line.html
Western Refining Inc. , a refinery
operator, amended its $800 million revolving credit agreement
and extended the maturity date.  The facility includes a $145 million tranche maturing on
May 31, 2012, and a $655 million tranche maturing on Jan. 1,
2015, the El Paso, Texas-based company said today in a statement
posted on its  website .  “We are pleased with the execution of this transaction as
it provides our company with additional financial flexibility
and liquidity in the coming years,”  Jeff Stevens , Western’s
chief executive officer, said in the statement.  The interest rate on the $145 million portion will remain
in a range of 3.75 percentage points to 4.5 percentage points
more than the London interbank offered rate, depending on
Western’s consolidated leverage ratio, according to the
statement.  The interest rate on the $655 million portion will
initially be 3.5 percentage points more than Libor, then will
fluctuate between 3 percentage points to 3.75 percentage points
based on unused availability, according to the statement.  Bank of America Corp.’s Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner &
Smith Inc. unit and Wells Fargo & Co. arranged the facility,
according to the statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Richard Bravo  in New York at 
 rbravo5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Faris Khan at 
 fkhan33@bloomberg.net . 